{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496560"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:50:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:50:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1383"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1383"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.68,0.1,0.1,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1383"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80243"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1383"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1383"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65537"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"733"},{"type":"tags","id":"878"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9060"},{"type":"tags","id":"9064"},{"type":"tags","id":"9339"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5462"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6587"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13148"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27422"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43841"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80243"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the General Practice Clinic with a two-year history of intermittent swallowing difficulties with associated chest pain. He has been increasingly coughing and gagging when eating and drinking both solids and liquids and has been treated for aspiration pneumonia three times in the past 12 months. He has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. The physical examination is otherwise unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA barium swallow study is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Zenker\u0027s diverticulum","Diffuse oesophageal spasm","Achalasia","Schatzki ring","Oesophageal web"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe barium swallow shows areas of narrowing and a spiralled appearance of the oesophagus. The term \u0027corkscrew oesophagus\u0027 is often applied. The history and the radiological features are consistent with a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Ediffuse oesophageal spasm\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition is characterised by uncoordinated contractions of the oesophagus, leading to difficulty swallowing and chest pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZenker\u0027s diverticulum\u003C/strong\u003E presents with a diverticulum arising from the posterior wall of the distal pharynx. An outpouching can be best seen on lateral view. This condition typically causes difficulty swallowing, regurgitation of undigested food, and halitosis, which are not prominent features in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAchalasia\u003C/strong\u003E classically results in dilatation of the oesophagus and narrowing of the distal oesophagus, resulting in the characteristic \u0027bird\u0027s beak\u0027 appearance. While it can cause dysphagia, the corkscrew appearance is not typical of achalasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ESchatzki ring\u003C/strong\u003E is a narrow band of tissue that can form at the lower end of the oesophagus. It typically appears as a thin, smooth narrowing on barium swallow, not the corkscrew appearance seen here. Schatzki rings are often associated with intermittent dysphagia to solids but not typically with chest pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eoesophageal web\u003C/strong\u003E is a thin membrane of tissue that protrudes into the oesophageal lumen, typically in the upper oesophagus. On barium swallow, it would appear as a thin, shelf-like projection, not the diffuse corkscrew pattern seen in this case. Oesophageal webs are often associated with iron deficiency anaemia (Plummer-Vinson syndrome) and primarily cause difficulty swallowing solids.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A corkscrew oesophagus is classically seen in barium studies of diffuse oesophageal spasm, a motility disorder of the oesophagus.","Diffuse oesophageal spasm typically presents with dysphagia and chest pain, and can lead to recurrent aspiration pneumonia."],"references":["Fonseca EK, Yamauchi FI, Tridente CF, Baroni RH. Corkscrew esophagus. Abdom Radiol (NY). 2017 Mar;42(3):985-986. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27832322/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65537"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1383"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16087"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16087"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7578d4a5-f16d-40c3-8f23-1d6842feeecb.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7578d4a5-f16d-40c3-8f23-1d6842feeecb.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":593}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"6553